# Assessment Strategy
assessment:
  primary: "Competency-based: Can student perform the task safely and correctly?"
  rubrics: "Beginning, Developing, Proficient, Advanced — emphasizing safety first"
  portfolio: "Students maintain records of projects completed and skills demonstrated"
  performance: "Real project completion with durability and appearance standards"

# Pedagogical Approach
pedagogical_approach: |
  Hands-on, scaffolded practice with real materials under supervision. Students work with
  actual tools, materials, and problems. Measurement before cutting. Planning before
  assembly. Safety protocols before tool use. Emphasis on why rules exist, not just
  memorization. Learning through making, fixing, and troubleshooting. Progression from
  simple to complex, foundation to specialization.

# Prerequisite Knowledge Detail
prerequisite_knowledge_detail: |
  MATH-101 (measurement, fractions, geometry, calculation) supports precision work across
  all modules. PHYS-101 (force, leverage, materials, electricity) provides conceptual
  foundation. ENGR-101 (technical drawing, systems thinking) supports project planning and
  understanding how systems interconnect. TRADE-101 does not require these but benefits
  significantly from them.

# Teaching Notes
teaching_notes: |
  Supervision is essential. Tools are dangerous. Safety is non-negotiable. Students need
  access to real tools, real materials, and real workspace. Module 1 (Tools, Safety,
  Workshop Practice) must come first and be refreshed constantly. Projects must produce
  real outcomes: a working birdhouse, a functional circuit, plumbing without leaks, a
  welded piece that holds. Emphasize diversity: trades skills are for everyone.

